 "Interpretation guide:"
if skewness_value > 1 or skewness_value < -1:
    print("Interpretation: Highly skewed.")
elif (skewness_value > 0.5 and skewness_value < 1) or (skewness_value < -0.5 and skewness_value > -1):

3.2 PERFORMING CATEGORICAL TO NUMERICAL CONVERSION

By making a copy, changing temperature from kelvin to celcius, and isolating numerical and categorical variables, this preprocesing workflow gets the dataset ready for modeling. While categorical weather features are resampled hourly using mean aggregation. A clean, model -ready feature set is created by merging the datasets , removing rows with missng traffic volume, eliminating unncessary coloumns, and one hot encoding categorical weather conditions.

In[]:
df_base = df_path_cleaned.copy()
df_base['temp_celsius'] = df_base['temp'] - 273.15


numeric_cols = df_base.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns.tolist()
categorical_cols = [col for col in ['weather_main', 'weather_description'] if col in df_base.columns]

df_numeric_resampled = df_base[numeric_cols].resample('h').mean()

df_categorical_resampled = df_base[categorical_cols].resample('h').agg(lambda x: x.mode()[0] if not x.mode().empty else np.nan)

df_processing = pd.merge(df_numeric_resampled, df_categorical_resampled,
                         left_index=True, right_index=True, how='left')

df_processing.dropna(subset=['traffic_volume'], inplace=True)

df_path_final_cleaned = df_processing.drop(columns=['weather_description'], errors='ignore')

df_encoded = pd.get_dummies(df_path_final_cleaned, columns=['weather_main'], prefix='weather', dtype=int)

print("Columns in the new encoded DataFrame:")
print(df_encoded.columns)
print("\nHead of the new weather indicator columns:")
print(df_encoded.filter(regex='^weather_').head())

The datetime index's temporal properties are extracted by this functionto enhance he dataset for modeling. It generates month to reflect seasonal trends, is_weekend as a binary indication for weekend traffic, day_of_week for weekdays effects and hour_of_day to capture hourly patterns. Forecasting accuracy is improved by these engineering features, which help the model better comprehend and learn reccurent traffic patterns influenced by time.

In[]:
df_path_cleaned['hour_of_day'] = df_path_cleaned.index.hour

4.2 ENCODING CYCLIC FEATURES

Using sine and cosine transformers, this code presrves theperiodic nature of cyclical temporal features.To ensure seamless transitions between boundary values (such as hour 23 to 0), hourly and weekly cycles are converted into hour_sin , hour_cos, day_sin, day_cos. In order to improve temporal pattern learning and better capture cyclic patterns for neural network modeling, the original hour_of_day and day_of_week coloumns are removed from the dataset.

In[]:
cycle_length_hour = 24
df_path_cleaned['hour_sin'] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * df_path_cleaned['hour_of_day'] / cycle_length_hour)
df_path_cleaned['hour_cos'] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * df_path_cleaned['hour_of_day'] / cycle_length_hour)


cycle_length_day = 7
df_path_cleaned['day_sin'] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * df_path_cleaned['day_of_week'] / cycle_length_day)
df_path_cleaned['day_cos'] = np.cos(2 * np.pi * df_path_cleaned['day_of_week'] / cycle_length_day)

df_path_cleaned = df_path_cleaned.drop(columns=['hour_of_day', 'day_of_week'])

print("\nDataFrame with Cyclic Features Encoded:")
print(df_path_cleaned[['hour_sin', 'hour_cos', 'day_sin', 'day_cos']].head())

4.3 CREATING HISTORICAL VALUE FOR TARGET VARIABLE USING LAG

In order to capture short-term daily, and weekly dependencies, this method generates lag features for traffic volume at intervals of 1 hour, 24 hours, and 168 hours. By identifying and eliminating NaNs caused by shifting, it creates a clean dataset with lagged characterstics, improving the model's capacity to recognize temporal patterns and increase forecasting accuracy

In[]:
target_col = 'traffic_volume'

df_path_cleaned['lag_1'] = df_path_cleaned[target_col].shift(1)

df_path_cleaned['lag_24'] = df_path_cleaned[target_col].shift(24)

df_path_cleaned['lag_168'] = df_path_cleaned[target_col].shift(168)

print(f"Number of NaNs created by shifting:\n{df_path_cleaned[['lag_1', 'lag_24', 'lag_168']].isnull().sum()}")

df_path_final = df_path_cleaned.dropna()

print(f"\nTotal rows before dropping NaNs that were created by lags: {len(df_path_cleaned)}")
print(f"Total rows after dropping NaNs that were created by lags: {len(df_path_final)}")

print("\nDataFrame with Lag Features:")
print(df_path_final[['traffic_volume', 'lag_1', 'lag_24', 'lag_168']].head())

4.4 CREATING ROLLING STATISTICS

In order to record both short-term and long-term trends in traffic volume, this code creates rolling statistics. Moving means(3,6,24 hours), a 3-hour median and 24 hour standard deviation are also computed.The model may take use of temporal patterns, trends, and voluantarily for better forecasting by eliminating NaNs, which guarantees clean data.

In[]:
target_col = 'traffic_volume'

df_path_final['rolling_mean_3h'] = df_path_final[target_col].rolling(window=3).mean()
df_path_final['rolling_mean_6h'] = df_path_final[target_col].rolling(window=6).mean()
df_path_final['rolling_mean_24h'] = df_path_final[target_col].rolling(window=24).mean()

df_path_final['rolling_median_3h'] = df_path_final[target_col].rolling(window=3).median()

df_path_final['rolling_std_24h'] = df_path_final[target_col].rolling(window=24).std()

df_path_final = df_path_final.dropna()

5 - DATA PREPRATION FOR RNN INPUT

5.1 DATA SPLITTING TRAIN-VALIDATION-TEST

In order to maintain chronological order "which was really crucial for this forecasting task, random split can't be used", this method uses a temporal split to divide the dataset into training, validation and test sets. To ensure data lekage and accurate predicting performance on unknown future traffic patterns, training data is used for model learning, validation for tweaking and early stopping, and test data for final evaluation

In[]:
test_size = 0.15
validation_size = 0.15

total_rows = len(df_encoded)
validation_start_index = int(total_rows * (1 - test_size - validation_size))
test_start_index = int(total_rows * (1 - test_size))

train_df = df_encoded.iloc[:validation_start_index]
validation_df = df_encoded.iloc[validation_start_index:test_start_index]
test_df = df_encoded.iloc[test_start_index:]

print(f"Data Split Summary:")
print(f"Total data points: {total_rows}")
print(f"Train shape: {train_df.shape} (from {train_df.index.min().strftime('%Y-%m-%d')} to {train_df.index.max().strftime('%Y-%m-%d')})")
print(f"Validation shape: {validation_df.shape} (from {validation_df.index.min().strftime('%Y-%m-%d')} to {validation_df.index.max().strftime('%Y-%m-%d')})")
print(f"Test shape: {test_df.shape} (from {test_df.index.min().strftime('%Y-%m-%d')} to {test_df.index.max().strftime('%Y-%m-%d')})")

5.2 PERFORMING SCALING FUNCTION via TENSORFLOW

In order to prepare the training , validation and test datasets for deep learning models, this code first transforms them into tensorflow tensors. After that, all features are acaled using keras. normalization layer, which is exclusively fitted on training data to avoid data leakage. Consistent feature ranges are ensured by applying same scaling to test and validation sets. By normalizig input magnitudes across all features, this step enhances model convergence, training stability and prediction accuracy.

In[]:
X_train_tf = tf.convert_to_tensor(train_df.values, dtype=tf.float32)
X_val_tf = tf.convert_to_tensor(validation_df.values, dtype=tf.float32)
X_test_tf = tf.convert_to_tensor(test_df.values, dtype=tf.float32)

normalizer = tf.keras.layers.Normalization(axis=-1)

normalizer.adapt(X_train_tf)

train_scaled_tf = normalizer(X_train_tf)
val_scaled_tf = normalizer(X_val_tf)
test_scaled_tf = normalizer(X_test_tf)

print("Data scaled using Keras Normalization layer.")
print(f"Shape of scaled training tensor: {train_scaled_tf.shape}")

Data scaled using Keras Normalization layer.
Shape of scaled training tensor: (28402, 19)

5.3 CREATING SEQUENCES FOR RNN

The scaled datasets are transformed into sequences appropriate for LSTM/RNN models, by this code. It creates input sequences of 48 previous timesteps (LOOKBACK) using sliding window technique in order to forecast the subsequent timestep (HORIZON). The scaled datasets are transformed into sequences appropriate for RNN?LSTM models by code.

In[]:
LOOKBACK = 48
HORIZON = 1

TARGET_COL_NAME = 'traffic_volume_log'

target_idx = train_df.columns.get_loc(TARGET_COL_NAME)

def create_sequences(df_scaled_tensor, lookback, horizon, target_column_index):
    """
    Converts a 2D TensorFlow tensor of scaled data into 3D sequences (X)
    and 1D targets (y) using the sliding window approach.
    """
    X, y = [], []
    data = df_scaled_tensor.numpy()

    for i in range(len(data) - lookback - horizon + 1):

        seq_x = data[i:(i + lookback)]
        X.append(seq_x)

        seq_y = data[i + lookback + horizon - 1, target_column_index]
        y.append(seq_y)

    return np.array(X), np.array(y)

X_train, y_train = create_sequences(train_scaled_tf, LOOKBACK, HORIZON, target_idx)
X_val, y_val = create_sequences(val_scaled_tf, LOOKBACK, HORIZON, target_idx)
X_test, y_test = create_sequences(test_scaled_tf, LOOKBACK, HORIZON, target_idx)


print(f"X_train shape: {X_train.shape} (Samples, Timesteps, Features)")
print(f"y_train shape: {y_train.shape} (Samples, Target Value)")
print(f"X_val shape: {X_val.shape}")
print(f"y_val shape: {y_val.shape}")
print(f"X_test shape: {X_test.shape}")
print(f"y_test shape: {y_test.shape}")

5.4 CLEANING SEQUENCES (REMOVING IF ANY NaN's ARE PRESENT)

In order to ensure clean, legitimate data for model training and evaluation, this code implements a function to exclude sequences containing NaN or infinite values from input (x) and target (y)

In[]:
def clean_sequences(X, y):


    if not isinstance(X, np.ndarray):
        X = np.array(X)
    if not isinstance(y, np.ndarray):
        y = np.array(y)


    is_valid_x = np.isfinite(X).all(axis=(1, 2))

    is_valid_y = np.isfinite(y)

    final_mask = is_valid_x & is_valid_y

    if not final_mask.all():
        print(f"Warning: Removing {np.sum(~final_mask)} samples due to NaNs/Infs.")

    return X[final_mask], y[final_mask]



X_train, y_train = clean_sequences(X_train, y_train)
X_val, y_val = clean_sequences(X_val, y_val)
X_test, y_test = clean_sequences(X_test, y_test)

6.4 PREDICTION AND INVERSE TRANSFORMATION

In order to assess predictions on the original traffic volume scale, this code reverses scaling and log transformation. To gauage model accuracy and error magnitude, this snippet of code computes MAE, MSE, RMSE.

In[]:
preds_scaled = model.predict(X_test)

target_mean_log = train_df[TARGET_COL_NAME].mean()
target_std_log = train_df[TARGET_COL_NAME].std()

preds_unscaled_log = (preds_scaled.flatten() * target_std_log) + target_mean_log
y_test_unscaled_log = (y_test * target_std_log) + target_mean_log

preds_original_scale = np.expm1(preds_unscaled_log)
y_test_original_scale = np.expm1(y_test_unscaled_log)

mae_original = np.mean(np.abs(y_test_original_scale - preds_original_scale))
mse_original = np.mean(np.square(y_test_original_scale - preds_original_scale))
rmse_original = np.sqrt(mse_original)

print(f"\nMAE on original scale: {mae_original:.2f}")
print(f"MSE on original scale: {mse_original:.2f}")
print(f"RMSE on original scale: {rmse_original:.2f}")

Here is what I concluded while developing this pipeline-

  • This method used early stopiing and early stopping snf learrning rate reduction callbacks to train the LSTM model. which makes it reliable for traffic forecasting.

  • Various hyperparameter tuning helped me understand the impact with minute detail changes creating huge loss and time differences

  • Comprehensive preprocessing was used, including cyclic encoding/rolling statistics,feature engineering missing value management and holiday/time features.

  • Data was scaled and converted to improve model stability and learning

  • dveloped 2 models to understand,a nd not blindly rely on single mode result

  • Using MAE,MSE,RMSE measures predictons were accurately evaluated by returning them to their original scale.

  • Showed how crucial sequential modeling and temporal aspects are to successful short term forecasting

  • For practical traffic predictions problems, pipelie offers a scalable solution.
